title: Electron Microscopy in Molecular Biophysics
subject: BIOPHYS
courseDescriptionLong: Designed to familiarize students with the physics of the design and application of electron optical systems, to permit them to read literature critically, and to allow them to execute experiments utilizing transmission and scanning electron microscopy. Discussion of electron image formation, image interpretation, and application of electron optics to problems in structural molecular and all biology. Discussion, demonstration, and practice of specimen preparative methods and electron microscopy in laboratory each week. Offered jointly with the Medical School as Biophysics 708.0.

title: Electron Microscopy in Cellular and Molecular Biology
subject: BIOPHYS
courseDescriptionLong: Designed to familiarize students with the preparation of a variety of biological specimens for analysis by electron microscopy, the use of electron optical systems, and interpretation of relevant literature. Topics include cellular and molecular specimen preparation, electron image formation and interpretation, contrast enhancement, damage limits, instrument operation and applications. Laboratory sessions provide students with hands-on operation of transmission and scanning electron microscopes, thin sectioning, autoradiography, immunocytochemistry, diffraction, and EM methods in molecular biology (molecular replication, negative staining, DNA spreading). Offered jointly with the Medical School as Physiology 708.0.

title: Molecular Biophysics: Simulation of Macromolecules
subject: BIOPHYS
courseDescriptionLong: Treatment of the principles and methods used for the simulation of macromolecules of biological interest. Protein and nucleic acid conformation and dynamics are emphasized. Empirical energy and molecular dynamics calculations as well as other approaches to molecular conformation and flexibility are described. Specific problems are discussed to illustrate the methodology. Examples include the cooperative mechanism of hemoglobin, the nature of reaction rate enhancement in enzyme catalysis, motional properties of proteins and nucleic acids, simulations of free energy changes in mutations, molecular recognition, and the properties of binding sites. Students are introduced to molecular graphics and to simulation methodology, and carry out an original project that makes use of these techniques. Biological Sciences 11 and one of the following: Chemistry 160, Biochemistry 61, Physics 143, or permission of instructor.

courseDescriptionLong: Introductory lectures by faculty members associated with the Biophysics program. Lectures are accompanied by three periods of instruction in laboratories of structural molecular biology, cell and membrane biophysics, molecular genetics and development, and physical biochemistry. Students normally spend each laboratory period in a different field. It is possible to undertake a suitable problem in mathematical biophysics in place of one of the three fields.
